 about how to improve the Squeeze-and-Excitation (SE) module.

First, the standard SE module applies global average pooling, which may lose some spatial information. To address this, we can incorporate both global average and max pooling, then concatenate their outputs before processing through the FC layers. This should capture more comprehensive features.

Secondly, using only linear layers might limit the expressiveness of the channel-wise interactions. Introducing depth-wise separable convolutions could help in capturing more intricate patterns within each channel.

Thirdly, the activation functions used after the FC layers can be optimized. Instead of ReLU followed by Sigmoid, perhaps using Swish or other advanced activations could yield better results.

Fourthly, adding dropout layers could prevent overfitting, especially when the network becomes deeper or the dataset is limited.

