```python
class SE_LN_Optimized(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, cin):
        super().__init__()
        self.gavg = nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1,1))  
        self.ln = nn.LayerNorm(cin)
        self.act = nn.Sigmoid()
        
    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        x = self.gavg(x)  # Shape: [batch, channels, 1, 1]
        x = x.squeeze(3).squeeze(2)  # Remove last two dimensions, shape becomes [batch, channels]
        x = self.ln(x)
        x = self.act(x)
        x = x.unsqueeze(2).unsqueeze(3)  # Restore last two dimensions, shape [batch, channels, 1, 1]
        return x * y
```

This version reduces the number of reshape operations by using `squeeze()` and `unsqueeze()` instead of `view()`, which may be more efficient as they avoid creating new tensors when possible.

Another potential optimization is to replace the sigmoid activation with a faster alternative, though in practice, sigmoid is already quite optimized.

Additionally, ensuring that all layers are properly initialized and that the model is moved to the appropriate device (CPU/GPU) can further enhance performance.

Finally, utilizing mixed precision training where applicable can also speed up computations without significantly affecting accuracy.
